Multiple Deprivation and Family Journeys Adults 2025

Author

Sophie Gemmen

Summary

In 2020, the Scottish Government updated the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation, the “standard approach to identify areas of multiple deprivation in Scotland.” The SIMD looks at several facets of quality of life within “data zones”, unified and comparable areas of analysis within traditional post codes. Some factors included in the index—and this analysis—are drug and alcohol use, income rates, and crime rates.

By overlaying data zones onto post codes and analysing where adults who use Family Journeys services live, Family Journeys has the opportunity to assess the living situations of their families and determine where more resources are needed.

Methodology

The following analysis uses data from three sources: Family Journeys’ Oasis database, the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation (2020) , and the postcode directory from the National Records of Scotland. The postcode directory provided data to connect the postcode information from Oasis to the corresponding data zone areas used in the SIMD. Additionally, data collected from MapIt was used to create the map of Scotland’s postcodes.

Data Zones to Postcodes

The SIMD calculates data based on “data zones”, which are smaller, standardised areas within postcodes. To conduct analysis in terms of postcodes, all statistics for data zones within postcodes were either added (number of adults and population estimate) or averaged (income deprivation rate, alcohol and drug hospitalisations, crime rate, and SIMD rank) to get a general, yet still standardised, understanding of the deprivation status within a postcode district.

Postcodes

Since 2021, Family Journeys has provided service to about 1800 adults, about 1500 of which had listed postcodes. Of those living in Scotland (where data for the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation covers), Family Journeys provides service to adults in 118 unique postcodes. Fifty of those unique postcodes are in Edinburgh, West Lothian, East Lothian, and Midlothian (any postcode beginning in “EH”).

The table below shows the number of unique regions where adults using Family Journeys services live. There are nine unique regions, with a vast majority of unique postcode districts coming from the “EH” area. Because nearly 95% of adults that use Family Journeys services live in the greater Edinburgh area, further analysis will only focus on EH postcodes.

Additionally, unique postcodes with only one adult have been removed from graphs and maps (but are no less important than the other adults). Single-adult postcodes accounted for 46 adults (or approximately 3%) with listed postcodes served by Family Journeys. Removing these data points increases clarity of visuals and allows for emphasis on the areas that utilize the largest amount of Family Journeys resources.

Variables

The table below is the data dictionary displaying the variables used in the following analysis.

Variable

Description

POSTCODE

Postcode district

ADULTS

Number of adults Family Journeys has served living in the postcode

INCOME

Percentage of people who are income deprived

POPULATION

2017 area population estimate for whole postcode

ALCOHOL

Hospital stays related to alcohol use: standardised ratio

DRUG

Hospital stays related to drug use: standardised ratio

CRIME

Recorded crimes of violence, sexual offences, domestic housebreaking, vandalism, drugs offences, and common assault per 10,000 people

RANK

SIMD rank for most (0) to least (6976) deprived data zone, averaged to represent the postcode

The Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation offers a wide range of data on postcodes, but for Family Journeys’ work, this analysis specifically focuses on factors involving alcohol use, drug use and crimes including violence and sexual offences. Additional factors like the percentage of people who are income deprived and the cumulative SIMD rank are also included in analyses.

Multiple Deprivation and FJ families

The figures below show the relationship between SIMD factors and the number of adults in a postcode that Family Journeys serves. Each point represents a unique postcode; the larger the point, the larger the number of Family Journeys adults living there.

Population Size and Geographic Location

The figure above shows the relationship between the population size estimate of an Edinburgh postcode and the number of adults Family Journeys has served in each postcode. The larger the Edinburgh postcode, the more people Family Journeys has supported in the area.

The figure below shows the number adults served by Family Journeys by postcode; the darker the colour, the more adults Family Journeys worked with in that postcode. Most service users are concentrated around the City of Edinburgh and the Bathgate area.

This mirrors a map (below) of the estimated population size in postcodes Family Journeys serves.

Note: a population denoted as “0” means that Family Journeys has not worked with an adult who lives in that postcode, not that there are no residents.

Income Deprivation

The figure above shows the relationship between the average percentage of people who income deprived in a postcode and the number of adults Family Journeys has served in the area. There is a rough correlation: Family Journeys has worked with more adults that come from postcodes with a higher percentage of people who are income deprived.

Alcohol Abuse

The figure above shows the relationship between the average number of alcohol-related hospital stays in a postcode and the number of adults Family Journeys has served in the area. There is again a rough correlation: Family Journeys has worked with more adults that come from postcodes with a higher average of alcohol-related hospital stays.

Drug Abuse

The figure above shows the relationship between the average number of drug-related hospital stays in a postcode and the number of adults Family Journeys has served in the area. Family Journeys has worked with more adults that come from postcodes with a higher average of drug-related hospital stays, though the relationship is not as strong as some other deprivation factors.

Recorded Crimes

Lastly, the figure above shows the relationship between the average number of recorded crimes in a postcode per 10,000 people and the number of adults Family Journeys has served since 2021. A clear relationship exists: Family Journeys serves more adults coming from postcodes with higher averages of recorded crimes. However, there are some large outliers with much higher average crime rates, while the majority of postcodes don’t exceed an average of 400 crimes.

The highest number of adults Family Journeys has served in a single postcode since 2021 is EH54, which also has the second largest population (EH4 has the first largest). However, by accounting for population size (shown in the PROPORTION column), EH24 has the highest number of adults using Family Journeys services (0.006). Additionally:

  • EH17 has the highest average income deprivation rate (0.17), and

  • EH17 has the highest average number of alcohol-related hospitalisations (139.23).

  • EH1 has the highest average number of drug-related hospitalisations (220.45), and

  • EH1 has the highest average crime rate (1649.29).

  • EH47 was ranked the lowest on the SIMD ranked scale, meaning overall EH47 faces the most amount of deprivation of the EH postcode districts.

Interactive Map

All the data provided in the table above is displayed in the interactive map below. The interactive map shows by color the number of adults Family Journeys has served since 2021, demonstrating the concentration of people FJ helps. Running your cursor over the map highlights the postcode and exact number of adults; to see more, click on the postcode of interest. A pop-up window will appear with data specific to the postcode: the average SIMD rank (ranks closer to zero imply higher levels of deprivation), the percentage of people income deprived, average hospital stays related to alcohol and drug-use, and the average number of crimes committed per 10,000 people.

Conclusion

This research demonstrates the relationship between population size, income deprivation, drug and alcohol use, and crime rates and the number of adults Family Journeys has provided for in each Edinburgh postcode. Generally, Family Journeys provides services to more individuals living in postcodes with higher rates of income deprivation, hospitalisations due to alcohol and drug abuse, and crime. With this data, Family Journeys could assess where resources need to be allocated and request funding accordingly.

Further analysis of these trends over time would be useful, as well as explorations of other deprivation factors from the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation and a statistical analysis of the significance of these trends.
